windward index
The objective of the maximum upwind slope (Sx) parameter was to quantify the extent of shelter or exposure provided by the terrain upwind of each pixel.
To determine the value of the Sx parameter, we examined all cells along a vector emanating from the cell of interest, determined the cell that had the greatest upward
slope relative to the cell of interest, and returned the slope between this shelter-defining cell and the cell of interest.
The selection of a maximum shelter-producing pixel based on slope is analogous to the determination of solar shading within the horizon function used in radiation modeling.
Negative Sx values indicated exposure relative to the shelter-defining pixel (i.e., the cell of interest was higher than the shelter-defining pixel). Theoretically,
increasingly negative Sx values correspond to greater constrictions on the approaching wind flow, leading to increasing wind speeds, while increasingly positive Sx
values correspond to larger and more proximal landscape obstacles, producing a greater degree of shelter and lower wind speeds.
Winstral et al: Spatial Snow Modeling of Wind-Redistributed Snow Using Terrain-Based Parameters (2002)
